        durability-value position between mainstream Whirlpool and budget Roper. Whirlpool's 2001 Amana
        acquisition (from Maytag Corporation, which had previously owned Amana separately) integrated
        Amana into Whirlpool's platform engineering while preserving the brand's durability-focused
        positioning. Current Amana refrigerators run simpler feature sets than mainstream Whirlpool or
        Maytag — fewer electronic controls, simpler defrost architectures, basic dispenser configurations,
        trimmed cabinet finish — which means fewer failure modes over the product's service life and
        lower per-repair costs when service is needed.
      </p>
      <p>
